# Rootstock System Invariants

Knowledge curation and distribution system for shared `.cursor` and `.claude` AI development environments — Tauri desktop app (Rust + SvelteKit), CLI (`graft-cli`), and AI skill. Core sync logic lives in the Rust `graft-core` crate used by both the desktop app and CLI.

**Hub**: The `scion` repo (`git@gitlab.com:cdo-office/scion.git`, public mirror at `github.com/MT-Hackathon/scion`) is the canonical knowledge store — it holds only `.cursor/` content, `graft-policy.json`, and `.rootstockignore`. The rootstock app repo connects to scion as a spoke project, just like every other project. `main` branch is the golden image; contributor branches (`contributor/{contributor}/{project_id}`) hold unreviewed submissions.

**Stack**: Desktop: Rust/Tauri 2.0 | Frontend: SvelteKit/Svelte 5 (adapter-static) | CLI: Rust/clap | Governance: scion repo's `.cursor/`

### The 9 Invariants

**1. Token Budget Governance**
Every session pays for every token in canonical. A change earns its place only if the AI will do something differently next session because it exists. Growth is borrowed against every future conversation, not paid once.

**2. Placement Determines Reachability**
Rules fire regardless of relevance (cost tokens always). Skills are found only when chosen. Placement is not organization — it's the activation mechanism. A skill's description is its only discovery surface.

**3. Integration Over Accumulation**
Overlapping skills tax discovery and fracture the knowledge network. Check for description overlap before creating new artifacts. Overlap = consolidation signal — integrate rather than append.

**4. Canonical Wins on Pull**
3-way merges in knowledge markdown produce blended intent with unclear ownership. Local improvements push upstream and get curated. If a local change is a live correction, push it before the next pull overwrites it.

**5. Policy-Driven Sync: Fail Closed**
Every synced file must have an explicit lifecycle classification in `graft-policy.json`. Unknown files MUST fail sync, not default to overwrite. Applies to all managed surfaces (`.cursor/`, `.claude/`).

**6. Trust Boundaries**
Tools sync, artifacts don't, secrets never. Pipeline scripts = shared infrastructure. Generated artifacts = per-user. Secrets = ignore (not protect). Protect = created once; ignore = rootstock has no knowledge.

**7. Portable Layer Converges; Protected Layer Diverges**
Rules 000–199 converge after curation. Rules 200+ diverge by design, never overwritten by `graft pull`. The policy boundary at 200 is the architectural seam between shared and local.

**8. Curation Authority**
AI recommends with specific rubric citations. Human approves. Decision is recorded with rationale. Default disposition: reject. Burden of proof on the evolution. Structured output schema from `curation-protocol.md` is mandatory.

**9. Script Portability**
PEP 723, `uv run --script`, no workspace-coupled imports. `uv run --script <path>` must succeed from any directory on any OS. Portability is what makes scripts executable by any instance in any connected environment.

